{
  "text": "Context matters. Neighborhood deprivation remained the persistent factor in our study, more so than the local smoking prevalence identified in other studies [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . At face value, it seems that socioeconomic hardship within the neighborhood context was the stronger factor. Yet smoking prevalence and deprivation are closely related, as are other potential determinants of smoking such as the distribution of tobacco outlets [CITATION_3] . Given their correlation in New Zealand, contextbased tobacco control policy options will be important and should include smoke-free parks and playgrounds and workplace bans to help alter perceptions about smoking normality, as well as options to change the ease of smoking, such as limiting access to tobacco outlets [CITATION_4] . Use of increased tobacco tax revenue to fund such interventions has high support among smokers across New Zealand [CITATION_5] . At a population level, New Zealand research indicates that increased tobacco prices have a net beneficial effect for persons living in the most deprived 30% of neighborhoods [CITATION_6] . Similarly, support for implementation of total smoking bans in households can increase awareness of smoking and secondhand smoke risks [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] as well as support persons seeking to quit [CITATION_9] . Such interventions can complement effective tobacco control interventions operating at the national population level (e.g., price and mass media) [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] .",
